<br/>
<div class="home-page main">
	<section class="grid-wrap" >
		<header class="grid col-full">
			<hr>
		</header>
		<div class="grid col-one-half mq2-col-full">
			<h3>Understand your business</h3>
			<p>It can be difficult to know what your customers like or not.</p>
			<p><dd>Especially if you have tens, hundreds, or thousands of items.</p></dd>
			<p><dd>To make it even more difficult, seasons, fashion, weather, ... are influencing your sales.<p></dd>
			<br/>
			<h5>Efficient Inventory is here to help you: one click and you're done!</h5>
			<p><dd>Items can be sorted by best / worst sales: just click on the column name</p></dd>
			<p><dd>You have 3 dedicated reports: "Best sellers", "Slow movers", and "End of life" to identify quickly your customers needs</p></dd>
		</div>
		<div class="grid col-one-half mq2-col-full">
			<img src="/images/best_sellers.jpg">
		</div>
	</section>
	<section class="grid-wrap" >
		<div class="grid col-two-thirds mq2-col-full">
			<h5>Do you know who this guy is?</h5>
			<p><dd>Vilfredo Pareto, economist of the 19th century.</p></dd>
			<p><dd>Let's avoid the mathematical part, and be straight to the point. He demonstrated that in every economic activity you have:</dd></p>
			<p>Best sellers:</p>
			<li><dd>5% of your articles making 40% of your turnover</li></dd>
			<li><dd>20% of your items making 80% of your turnover</li></dd>
			<br/>
			<p>Slow movers:</p>
			<li><dd>80% of your items making only 20% of your turnover</li></dd>
			<li><dd>40% of your turnover making only 5% of your turnover</li></dd>
			<br/>
			<p>In Efficient Inventory, we are using these results to show you these categories, so that you know in real time and for every article, in which category it is.</p>
		</div>
		<div class="grid col-one-third mq2-col-full">
			<img src="/images/vilfredo_pareto.jpg">
		</div>
	</section>	
</div>


